'''Benjamin Hobson''' (1816–1873) (Chinese：合信) was a [[Protestantism in China|Protestant]] [[Medical missions in China|medical missionary]] who served with the [[London Missionary Society]] in [[imperial China]] during its [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] [[list of Chinese dynasties|dynasty]]. His ''Treatise on Physiology'', reproducing and elaborating on work by [[William Cheselden]], helped revolutionize Chinese and later [[Tokugawa Japan|Japanese]] medical understanding and treatment.

==Life==
Hobson was born in 1816 in [[Welford, Northamptonshire|Welford]], [[Northamptonshire]], in [[England]].{{sfn|''BDCC''}} He graduated from [[University College London|London University]] with a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB]] and passed an examination as a [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]].<ref name=wf>{{harvp|Wylie|1867|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=jRQQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA125 125]}}.</ref>

Joining the [[London Missionary Society]] as a [[Medical missions in China|medical missionary]] to the [[Qing Empire]], he departed with his wife Jane Abbey Hobson and Messrs Legge and [[William Milne (missionary)|Milne]] on {{ship||Eliza Stewart|1833 ship|2}}. It left London on 28 July 1839, and reached [[Anyer]] on 12 November 12 and [[Portuguese Macao|Macao]] on 18 December. Assisted by [[Elijah Bridgman]], Hobson found a residence and joined the local [[Medical Missionary Society]]. Its hospital reopened on August 1, 1840. When [[William Lockhart (priest)|William Lockhart]] left for [[Zhoushan]] at the end of the month and Dr Diver retired from poor health soon afterwards, Hobson was left in sole charge of its operation. In early 1843, he left to establish an MMS hospital in [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]. This opened to patients on June 1<ref name=wf/> and the demand for its services so outstripped both expectations and capacity that he relied heavily on help from Chinese assistants. This led him to consider how to explain western medical training to the Chinese,{{sfn|''BDCC''}} then reliant on often [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] [[traditional Chinese medicine|traditional medicine]].

In 1845, his wife's health was so poor that they left for Britain in July but she died while at anchor off Dungeness on December 22. Left with a young son and daughter,<ref name=wf/> he married Rebecca Morrison,{{sfn|''BDCC''}} the daughter of his fellow Chinese missionary [[Robert Morrison (missionary)|Robert]], while in England. He returned with her and Mr Hirschberg on the ''Hugh Walker''. This left Britain on March 11, 1847, and reached Hong Kong on July 27, whereupon he resumed direction of its hospital.<ref name=wf/>

He visited [[Guangzhou]] ([[Postal Map Romanization|then known]] as "Canton") with Mr Gillespie in October 1847 and moved there the next February, operating a clinic out of his residence. In April, he opened a pharmacy and, in June, purchased the house on Kum-Le-Fo<ref name=ws>{{harvp|Wylie|1867|p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=jRQQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA126 126]}}.</ref> ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|金|利|埠}}}}, ''Jīnlì Bù'', <small>{{abbr|lit|literally}}.</small>&nbsp;"Golden Benefit Wharf") in the [[Xiguan|western suburbs]]<ref name=gib/> for use as the Missionary Hospital<ref name=ws/> or {{nowrap|Wo Ai}} Clinic {{nowrap|(<small>[[traditional characters|t]]</small> {{lang|zh|{{linktext|惠|愛|醫館}}}},}} {{nowrap|<small>[[simplified characters|s]]</small> {{lang|zh|{{linktext|惠|爱|医馆}}}},}} ''Huìài Yīguǎn'').<ref name=gib>{{citation |contribution-url=http://mall.cnki.net/magazine/Article/GDSI199901009.htm |contribution=合信的《全体新论》与广东士林 |title=''《广东史志》'' |date=1999 |publisher=CNKI }}. {{zh icon}}</ref> While there, he was assisted by the Chinese ministers and missionaries [[Liang Fa]] and [[Zhou Xue]]. At the end of 1854, he traveled to [[Shanghai International Settlement|Shanghai]] for a five-week rest for health reasons. He and his family were forced to evacuate to Hong Kong in October 1856 on account of the onset of the [[Second Opium War]].<ref name=ws/>

The missionary community of Shanghai prevailed upon him to return in February 1857 and he took Dr Lockhart's place at their hospital when Lockhart returned to England at the end of that year. His eldest son took work with a merchant house, but the rest of the family returned with him to Europe, reaching England in March 1859. His health not permitting his return to China, he then resided at Clifton and [[Cheltenham]].<ref name=ws/> He died at [[Forest Hill, London|Forest Hill]] near [[London]] in 1873.{{sfn|''BDCC''}}

==Works==
Benjamin Hobson published the following works:<ref name=wste>{{harvp|Wylie|1867|pp=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=jRQQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA126 126–8]}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Chinese titles are given in modern [[traditional characters]], some of which—such as those preceded by the [[糹|silk radical]]—vary slightly from their 19th-century forms. Romanizations include both modern [[pinyin]] and the contemporary [[romanization of Chinese|romanization]]. Translations are [[Alexander Wylie (missionary)|Wylie]]'s.<ref name=wste/>}}

