{{about||the town of ancient Argolis|Mideia (Argolis)|the town of ancient Boeotia|Mideia (Boeotia)|the town in Eastern Thrace|Kıyıköy}} In [[Greek mythology]], '''Mideia'''{{Pronunciation-needed}} or '''Midea''' ([[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]]: Μιδειη) may refer to:
*Midea, a [[Phrygia]]n slave, mother of [[Licymnius]] by [[Electryon]].<ref>Pseudo-[[Apollodorus of Athens|Apollodorus]], ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 2. 4. 5</ref> *Midea, a [[nymph]], mother of Aspledon by [[Poseidon]]. The town [[Lebadea]] was believed to have previously been named Mideia after her.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 9. 38. 9 - 9. 39. 1, citing [[Chersias]].</ref> *Midea, one of the [[Danaids]]. She married (and killed) Antimachus, son of [[Aegyptus]].<ref>[[Hyginus]], ''Fabulae'', 170</ref> *Midea, daughter of [[Aloeus]] and [[eponym]] of a city in [[Argos]].<ref>[[Stephanus of Byzantium]], s. v. ''Mideia''</ref>
