The '''Rashtriya Sikh Sangat''' (lit. "National Sikh Association") is an India-based [[Sikhism|Sikh]] organization with about 450 units predominantly in the states of Rajasthan, Punjab, Delhi, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh and Maharashtra.<ref name="Dogra"/> Rashtriya Sikh Sangat was inspired by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] organization [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] and has aimed to unite Hindus and Sikhs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sanjeev Kelkar|title=Lost Years of the RSS|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNiGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181|year=2011|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0762-0|pages=181–182}}</ref>
The organization has also pressed for Sikh rights in many states in India, including Jammu & Kashmir where it demanded that the state should recognize National Commission of Minorities jurisdiction and protect Sikhs as minorities in the state.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/rashtriya-sikh-sangat-members-meet-jk-governor-116010501211_1.html Rashtriya Sikh Sangat members meet JK Governor], Business Standard (January 5, 2016)</ref>
In 2004, the leader of the [[Akal Takht]] declared that the Sangat to be "anti-Sikh". It forbade all Sikhs from having any association with it.<ref name="Dogra">{{cite news|last1=Dogra|first1=Chander Suta|title=Ex-militants to riot package: RSS reaches out to Punjab via Sikh arm|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ex-militants-to-riot-package-rss-reaches-out-to-punjab-via-sikh-arm/|accessdate=16 January 2017|work=The Indian Express|date=17 December 2014}}</ref>
In 2009, [[Babbar Khalsa]], a Sikh militant group assassinated Rulda Singh, the president of the Rashtriya Sikh Sangat, in [[Patiala]].<ref name="Dogra"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101214/punjab.htm#1| title= Rulda Singh’s killers to stand trial in UK, British police team arrives to collect evidence|work=tribuneindia.com}}</ref>
In 2014, the Rashtriya Sikh Sangat elected Gurcharan Singh Gill as its president.<ref name="Dogra"/>
